estic policy debates as well as which factors determine how much power it can exert in different national environments. The case study analysis also reveals why western democracies have implemented different models of recognition (marriage vs. registered partnership vs. unregistered cohabitant).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil unionszEurope, WesternxHistory. 0aCivil unionszNorth AmericaxHistory. 0aHomosexualityzEurope, WesternxHistory. 0aHomosexualityzNorth AmericaxHistory. 0aSame-sex marriagezEurope, WesternxHistory. 0aSame-sex marriagezNorth AmericaxHistory. 0aSame-sex marriage. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Freedom.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aEuropean SSU norm.  aEuropean polity.  aGermany.  aLGBT rights.  aNetherlands.  aUnited States.  agay male couples.  ainternational human rights.  ainternational policy diffusion.  alesbian couples.  aregistered partnership.  arelationship recognition.  asame-sex unions.  asoft-law norm.  asupportive policy elites.  awestern democracies.1 aKollman, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611221740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526112217423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526112217/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles